label.value: larval abdominal posterior commissure

value.value: Posterior-most of the two main midline-crossing commissures that develop in the posterior half of each abdominal neuromere, except for a9 which only has an anterior commissure. The posterior commissure contains fewer fibers than the anterior commissure and is located approximately at the level of the posterior neuromere boundary.

label.value: presumptive embryonic/larval peripheral nervous system

value.value: The sum of all the structures in the embryo that will develop into the embryonic/larval peripheral nervous system.

label.value: proneural cluster

value.value: An equivalence group of the neurectoderm where all cells can, although only one will, become a neural progenitor cell.

label.value: sensory mother cell

value.value: Precursor cell that can give rise to all the neuronal and support cells that form a peripheral sense organ.

label.value: C1 chordotonal organ precursor cell

label.value: peripheral nervous system precursor cluster

label.value: embryonic glioblast

value.value: Glioblast of the embryo.

label.value: embryonic dorsal procephalic subperineural glial cell

value.value: Glial cell of the embryo that arises at the dorsoposterior edge of the protocerebrum (Hartenstein et al., 1998). At early stage 12 there are 2-3 cells, and this number increases to 5-6 (Hartenstein et al., 1998). Until stage 15, cells of this cluster stay together in a wedge-shaped formation, but later spread out to cover the dorso-posterior surface of the supraesophageal ganglion (Hartenstein et al., 1998). Most of these cells become larval surface glia, but some may become cell body glia (Hartenstein et al., 1998; Hartenstein et al., 2011).

label.value: embryonic ventral procephalic subperineural glial cell

value.value: Glial cell of the embryo that arises near the boundary between the protocerebrum and deutocerebrum (Hartenstein et al., 1998). There are around 12 of these cells by embryonic stage 12 (Hartenstein et al., 1998). During stage 12, cells of this cluster spread out to cover the anterior and lateral surface of the deutocerebrum and basal protocerebrum (Hartenstein et al., 1998). Most of these cells develop into larval subperineurial glia, but some may become cell body glia (Hartenstein et al., 1998).

label.value: embryonic basal procephalic longitudinal glial cell

value.value: Glial cell of the embryo that arises close to the boundary between the tritocerebrum and deutocerebrum (Hartenstein et al., 1998). There are only two or three of these cells early in stage 11, but they increase in number to around 20 by the end of stage 12 (Hartenstein et al., 1998). They spread out dorsally and ventrally, at the medial surface of the brain neuropil, reaching the precursor to the brain connective dorsally and the connectives joining the brain to the VNC ventrally (Hartenstein et al., 1998; Omoto et al., 2015). These cells become larval neuropil glia (Hartenstein et al., 1998).

definition.value: Thought to descend from Td7 neuroblast based on its position and gcm expression, but no direct evidence (Hartenstein et al., 2011; Omoto et al., 2015).
